#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

cat <<'EOF'
Composer helper commands available in this container
===================================================

composer-help
  Lists the available Composer helper commands.

composer-validate
  Validates composer.json and composer.lock with:
    composer validate --strict

composer-install-dev
  Installs dependencies for development using composer.lock.
  Includes require and require-dev dependencies.
  Typical usage after cloning the project or switching branches.

composer-audit
  Runs Composer security audits.
  Audits both:
    - all dependencies, including dev dependencies
    - production dependencies only with --no-dev

composer-security-check
  Runs a broader dependency/security check:
    - Composer version
    - PHP version
    - composer validate --strict
    - composer check-platform-reqs
    - composer audit
    - composer audit --no-dev
    - composer show --direct
    - composer outdated --direct

composer-outdated
  Shows outdated direct dependencies.
  Also checks common Symfony project namespaces:
    - symfony/*
    - doctrine/*
    - api-platform/*

composer-require vendor/package[:version]
  Adds a production dependency.
  Runs validation and audit afterwards.
  Example:
    composer-require lexik/jwt-authentication-bundle

composer-require-dev vendor/package[:version]
  Adds a development dependency.
  Runs validation and audit afterwards.
  Example:
    composer-require-dev phpstan/phpstan

composer-update-safe vendor/package [vendor/package ...]
  Updates selected packages only.
  Refuses to run a global composer update without explicit package names.
  Uses --with-all-dependencies.
  Example:
    composer-update-safe symfony/security-bundle

composer-update-patch
  Updates dependencies with Composer's --patch-only option.
  Useful for conservative maintenance updates.
  Always review composer.lock afterwards.

composer-why-package vendor/package
  Explains why a package is installed and shows package details.
  Example:
    composer-why-package psr/log

composer-install-prod-check
  Checks that production dependencies can be installed.
  Runs composer install --no-dev and composer audit --no-dev.

  Warning:
    In a development container, this may remove dev dependencies from vendor/.
    Prefer running it in CI or in a temporary container.

Recommended daily workflow
==========================

After cloning the project:
  composer-install-dev

Before committing dependency changes:
  composer-security-check

Add a production dependency:
  composer-require vendor/package

Add a development dependency:
  composer-require-dev vendor/package

Update a package for security:
  composer-update-safe vendor/package

Check what is outdated:
  composer-outdated

Important Composer rules
========================

Use composer install for normal work, CI and Docker builds.

Use composer update only when you intentionally want to change dependency versions.

Do not run a global composer update casually.

Always review changes in:
  composer.json
  composer.lock
EOF
